 Georgia, focusing on the historic Our Lady of Lourdes Catholic Church in the Old Fourth Ward. Our Lady of Lourdes is a neighbor of major historic Black Protestant churches in the city, including Ebenezer Baptist Church, a block away, which during the Civil Rights era was the pulpit of Martin Luther King Jr. Featuring archival and oral history sources, the book examines the religious and cultural life of the parishioners of Our Lady of Lourdes Catholic Church, showing how this Black Catholic congregation fit into the overall religious ecology of the neighborhood. Examining Our Lady of Lourdes in relation to these larger Black Protestant congregations helps to illuminate whether and how they were shaped by their place at a center of the civil rights struggle, and how religious change and social change intersect.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / African American .2bisacsh  aAfrican American history.  aAfrican Americans.  aAnti-Catholicism.  aArchdiocese of Atlanta.  aAtlanta, Georgia.  aAuburn Avenue.  aBig Bethel African Methodist Church.  aBlack Catholics.  aCatholic schools.  aCivil Rights Movement.  aDesegregation.  aEbenezer Baptist Church.  aFrancis E. Hyland.  aGeorge Stallings.  aIgnatius Lissner.  aKatherine Drexel.  aLiturgical reform.  aLiturgical renewal.  aMissal of Paul VI.  aPaul Hallinan.  aRacism.  aReligious studies.  aRoman Catholic Church.  aSacrosanctum Concilium.  aSchool desegregation.  aSecond Vatican Council.  aSisters of the Blessed Sacrament.  aSlavery.  aThomas Donnellan.  aWheat Street Baptist Church.  aWomen religious.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08